50|$|At {{the federal}} level, Megan's Law {{requires}} persons convicted of sex crimes against children to notify {{local law enforcement}} of any change of address or employment after release from custody (prison or psychiatric facility). The <b>notification</b> <b>requirement</b> may be imposed for a fixed period of time—usually at least ten years—or permanently. Some states may legislate registration for all sex crimes, even if no minors were involved. It is a felony in most jurisdictions to fail to register or fail to update information.|$|E
